        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Vince Morgan, SIPA ’06, director of the Housing Development Fund Corporation Resource Center at the West Harlem Development Corporation, was terminated without severance, he said, by the WHDC board of directors on Jan. 15."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Interviews and documents reviewed by Spectator show that Morgan’s termination is part of a larger history of workplace conflict at the WHDC and a reluctance by organization leaders to spend organization funds on initiatives for HDFC residents, who are often low-income and have faced financial burdens for years."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The organization’s resource center, where Morgan served as the head for two years, provides support to affordable housing co-ops in West Harlem. Morgan previously spent five years on the WHDC board."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "According to Morgan, his conflict with the WHDC leadership was twofold: In February 2024, he filed a whistleblower complaint against Executive Director Zead Ramadan, alleging he created a toxic work environment, after recording comments Ramadan made at work. Morgan also criticized Ramadan’s leadership of the WHDC, claiming that Ramadan impeded his ability to help HDFC residents by consistently declining his funding proposals."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“There’s no mechanism to sort of complain or provide any oversight over it, which is why I ultimately got fired, because I started asking questions about this erratic management style,” Morgan told Spectator. “I think that anyone can understand, listening to those recordings and seeing the leadership that he’s shown over the past few years in the organization, is that he’s not qualified to be the executive director.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Both Ramadan and Milton Tingling, chairman of the WHDC board, declined to comment, citing that the organization is anticipating litigation related to the issue."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>The HDFC Resource Center</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The WHDC is a product of the Community Benefits Agreement, a 49-page document signed by Columbia in 2009 in which the University promised the surrounding community $170 million in benefits over 36 years in lieu of paying property taxes."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Among those benefits was the creation of the WHDC, an organization meant to distribute $76 million in funds to the neighborhood to minimize the negative impacts of the University’s expansion into West Harlem, primarily through economic development."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The CBA earmarks some of these funds for the creation of an HDFC Resource Center that would “provide education, advocacy, information and technical assistance to CD 9’s HDFC cooperatives and other properties.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In New York City, HDFCs are a unique type of housing co-op in which residents, who are low or middle income, are responsible for the building’s upkeep. West Harlem has the most HDFCs of any neighborhood in New York City, but these buildings often face financial hurdles."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<i>[Read more: </i><a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/city-news/2024/04/15/cb9-boasts-the-most-hdfcs-in-new-york-city-but-undisclosed-maintenance-costs-threaten-residents-homeownership/\"><i>CB9 boasts the most HDFCs in New York City, but undisclosed maintenance costs threaten residents’ homeownership</i></a><i>]</i>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Paula Soto, whose mother raised her in a West Harlem HDFC and now owns the unit herself, said HDFCs have a unique need for legal assistance."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I think it just has to do with training,” Soto said. “You tend to have, in general, not always, an older group of tenants who may not be technologically savvy, who may not necessarily speak the language.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan said HDFCs are on “the precipice of some really challenging times.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“A lot of the maintenance and development issues to keep these buildings running with populations that are, in many cases, financially stressed already, they’re all just coming due for major renovations,” he said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan said he held two community events to address these needs in 2023, the first on the general problems faced by HDFCs and the second on compliance with an environmental regulation called Local Law 97."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Soto attended the first forum, where she said she was able to find a more affordable insurance company for her building."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We do need resources, in terms of human beings that we can go to and ask questions, or if it is like a workshop or classes, be able to take classes, be able to have access to professionals,” Soto said. “Being able to have a space with the resources would be absolutely game changing.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "She was disappointed, however, when the programming did not continue after the forums."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Michael Palma Mir, an HDFC advocate who helped found the HDFC Coalition in 1992, said he had a similar experience. He worked with Morgan prior to the events in 2023, but did not notice any work from the resource center after 2023."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“He would call me from time to time, ask me questions, but he was trying to get the lay of the land,” Palma Mir said. “After we worked on the two issues, the issues of not only the insurance, but also Local Law 97, I haven’t heard back from him at all.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Palma Mir was part of the group that proposed the HDFC Resource Center clause for the CBA 16 years ago. He said he told Morgan to “focus on the easy things to do” for HDFCs."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We need good plumbers, we need good attorneys, we need conflict resolution, we need someone to advise on best practices to run an HDFC,” Palma Mir said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan continued to assist individual buildings according to HDFC residents, but the HDFC Resource Center never became an established office space of its own, nor did it offer formal legal advice."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Signe Mortensen, co-chair of Community Board 9’s housing, land use, and zoning committee, has called for the WHDC to provide similar resources."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“Under the CBA the WHDC can: grant funding to create, provide and maintain an accessible bi-lingual HDFC Resource Center that shall be established to support and preserve the HDFC community and other properties,” Mortensen wrote in a statement to Spectator. “The area HDFC’S are dismayed that the WHDC has yet to create this ‘Resource Center’ to assist in maintaining these valued properties.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>A ‘stockpile’ of WHDC funds</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan said he was prevented from providing this kind of assistance by Ramadan and Tingling. As director of the HDFC Resource Center, he said he expected to receive a budget of his own, and proposed using these funds to create a grant or loan program for buildings with HDFC residents. He said that Ramadan and Tingling rejected this proposal, directing him to focus on “existing resources from other services that did not have a cost.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“Every time I would ask for any type of financial resource, I would be blocked,” Morgan said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan also said that Ramadan and Tingling prevented the Resource Center from offering legal advice to HDFC residents."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Spectator obtained a recording of a February 2024 meeting between Tingling, Ramadan, and Morgan in which Morgan proposed bringing in retro commissioning agents from the city to help HDFC owners ensure their buildings complied with New York City’s new environmental law, Local Law 97."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In the recording, Tingling told Morgan that this kind of assistance would be “overstepping.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I don’t want the resource center taking on the responsibility or perceptually the community thinking it’s our responsibility to get it done,” Tingling said. “This is also an exercise in having these people work together and come together.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan criticized Tingling’s reluctance to spend WHDC funds on legal advisors."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“They don’t want to do anything other than the perfunctory turkey giveaways,” he said. “For whatever reason, they are trying to stockpile that money.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "As of 2023, the WHDC’s annual operating expenses totaled $3.7 million, which included a $733,239 property lease, a $212,423 salary for Ramadan, and a $145,923 salary for Morgan, according to the organization’s tax returns. Meanwhile, the organization allocated about $2.5 million in grants per year, the most common grant size being $10,000. At the end of 2023, the initial $76 million endowment was down to $55 million."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan worries that operating costs will continue to eat up the endowment before it can be used to spur economic development in West Harlem."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“If you’ve got a piggy bank of $50 million, wouldn’t you figure out some plan of action to leverage that money to raise additional money for specific programming moving forward?” Morgan said. “If not, then the organization just ceases to exist after 10 years.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The WHDC received its last installment of funds from Columbia in 2024, and some of the benefits administered by the WHDC are set to expire in 2045."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>‘Unfit to lead’</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In conjunction with the conflict over the use of WHDC funds, Morgan opposed Ramadan’s workplace behavior, which he said was antisemitic and offensive. After audio recording Ramadan without his knowledge for around a month, Morgan filed a complaint against him in February 2024 to Chairman Tingling alleging that he created a toxic work environment."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Spectator obtained recordings of Ramadan submitted in Morgan’s complaint, one of which mentions Congressman Adriano Espaillat, who is involved in the WHDC and is responsible for nominating one of its board members."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "On Feb. 14, 2024, Ramadan said that Espaillat had set aside new affordable housing units to be given to Latino residents because he “wants to make sure that Dominicans control that area forever.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“The Democrats were like, look, we need fucking voters to kill the Republicans once and for all down the line. We have to add two more million,” Ramadan said. “They’re gonna all have babies, they’re all gonna be American citizens, and within a generation, we should be able to knock out the Republicans once and for all.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Espaillat’s office did not respond to requests for comment."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "According to a recording taken on Jan. 24, 2024, Ramadan told Morgan that Deputy Borough President Aya Keefe, who works under Manhattan Borough President Mark Levine and was formerly on the WHDC board, is Levine’s “handler.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“She runs his ship because she’s Israeli, with a heavy accent, she gets the fucking money for Mark Levine,” Ramadan said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In a recording from the day before, Ramadan also called Ross Frommer, vice president for government and community affairs for Columbia, a “messy fucking Zionist Jewish guy who has done nothing in two decades for Washington Heights.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Morgan submitted these recordings to Tingling, along with a formal complaint against Ramadan. Four months later, Tingling acknowledged “dropping the ball” on addressing these complaints in an email Morgan obtained by Spectator."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In May 2024, Congressman Espaillat appointed Larry English, former chairman of Community Board 9, to the WHDC Board. Upon joining the board, English put forth a motion to hire outside counsel to look into Morgan’s complaints, but the motion was dismissed. On Aug. 22, 2024, English filed a formal complaint against the WHDC board for improperly investigating Morgan’s complaints against Ramadan."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“The investigation of the allegations of antisemitism and creating a toxic work environment against the Executive Director is tainted,” English wrote. “It was further tainted when the Board unanimously voted to reject hiring external counsel and instead allowed the Chairman to appoint the Vice-Chair of the Board, who is now acting as an avatar for Chairman Tingling to remain in control of the investigation.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Like Morgan, English associated Ramadan’s alleged toxic work environment with a general inability to lead the organization properly."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“The Board does not have a strategic plan in place to grow the endowment,” English wrote. “As Columbia has made its final payment, the lack of a strategic plan threatens the future of the WHDC. Moreover, I add my voice to the employees who have raised serious concern about the ED’s ability to lead the organization.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "English sent his complaint to Tingling as board chairman, as well as Rep. Espaillat, whose office English represents."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "On Oct. 10, 2024, Tingling emailed the Board to arrange a meeting “for the purpose of removing Board member Larry English,” according to a copy of the email obtained by Spectator. According to Morgan, Espaillat intervened in English’s removal by cancelling the meeting the day before. English continues to serve on the WHDC Board."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>A pattern for the WHDC</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In addition to English’s attempted removal in October and Morgan’s termination in January, former Executive Director Kofi Boateng said Tingling used a similar process to remove him in 2020 after an interpersonal conflict. Boateng believes his removal was retaliatory."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“The process leading to my exit, which was engineered by the same people,” Boateng said. “Milton Tingling and Zead Ramadan.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Boateng had invested $2 million of the WHDC’s affordable housing fund in a housing project in Central Harlem with a certain return on investment. According to Boateng, after Tingling approved his use of the money, he accused Boateng of lying about the return on investment. Boateng refuted the accusation, and around one year later, the developer returned the $2 million plus interest to the WHDC."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Before the money had been returned, Tingling created an executive committee to discuss Boateng’s housing project but excluded him, Boateng said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“He created an executive committee of which Zead was the member, and they held several meetings to conspire about me without me being present,” Boateng said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Boateng’s entire staff resigned in protest of his termination, he said. When Boateng was informed of the recent events at WHDC, he said he was not surprised."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“Zead colluded with Tingling … and Tingling rewarded Zead with my job, not based on qualification, but based on him colluding with him,” Boateng said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "John Betancourt, who served as the WHDC’s chief compliance officer from 2021 to 2023, said the board’s selection process of Ramadan as executive director had been “unusual” because it appeared to him that they were not looking for any other applicants."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“It was more of a very superficial process, and then they made Mr. Ramadan the executive director, and again, I don’t think that he had anything in his background at all that would have suggested that he would have that skill set,” Betancourt said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "He said that Tingling and Ramadan “seem to be highly coordinated, but they may not be providing each other with the appropriate oversight.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<b>The future of the Resource Center</b>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "After English was nearly removed from the board for raising concerns about Ramadan, Morgan said Rep. Espaillat’s office demanded the WHDC conduct an outside investigation."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "A human resources specialist was hired to investigate Morgan’s complaints and interview the staff in January, and she presented her report to the board on Jan. 15, the same day the board voted to fire Morgan without severance. His termination letter states that the decision was not related to his grievances with Ramadan."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I was told when I was hired that I was going to have the power and the resources and be empowered to try and do something significant to help these buildings, and I was given nothing,” Morgan said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "As the WHDC looks for a new director for the HDFC Resource Center, Palma Mir is hoping for someone who already has HDFC expertise—ideally from being an HDFC shareholder themself."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I’m hoping that they can find someone who can really live out the division of the resource center as it was originally intended in the Community Benefits Agreement. To be a real resource, to be a resource for HDFCs,” Palma Mir said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Soto emphasized the potential that HDFCs hold for their residents, and said she hopes the organization will give HDFC residents the training they need in order to stay in New York City."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "She said that HDFC ownership “really changed the trajectory of my life.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“That is what the HDFC offers, more than anything,” Soto said. “It offers a way to really climb out of poverty.”"
          },
          {
